04972nam a22007335i 9780231555104DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20232023nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315551047 a10.7312/verc203542doi  a(DE-B1597)642751  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aGF71b.V47 2023 7aSCI0920002bisacsh04a304.2/5223/eng202211031 aVerchick, Rob, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Octopus in the Parking Garage :bA Call for Climate Resilience /cRob Verchick. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource :b8 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPART I Understanding Resilience -- t1 Let’s Talk About the Octopus -- t2 Adapt or Die -- t3 Sprawling Brains and Rubber Arms -- t4 Climate and Caste -- t5 Believing Is Seeing -- tPART II: DOING RESILIENCE -- t6 Moonshot on the Bayou -- t7 Lights Out -- t8 Flash! Crack! Boom! -- t9 Yuccas, Gardeners, and Zookeepers -- t10 The Octopus’s Garden -- t11 The Long Goodbye -- t12 Persist and Prevail -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOne morning in Miami Beach, an unexpected guest showed up in a luxury condominium complex’s parking garage: an octopus. The image quickly went viral. But the octopus—and the combination of infrastructure quirks and climate impacts that left it stranded—is more than a funny meme. It’s a potent symbol of the disruptions that a changing climate has already brought to our doorsteps and the ways we will have to adjust.Rob Verchick examines how we can manage the risks that we can no longer avoid, laying out our options as we face climate breakdown. Although reducing carbon dioxide emissions is essential, we need to adapt to address the damage we have already caused. Verchick explores what resilience looks like on the ground, from early humans on the savannas to today’s shop owners and city planners. He takes the reader on a journey into the field: paddling through Louisiana’s bayous, hiking in one of the last refuges of Joshua trees in the Mojave Desert, and diving off Key Largo with citizen scientists working to restore coral reefs. The book emphasizes disadvantaged communities, which bear the brunt of environmental risk, arguing that building climate resilience is a necessary step toward justice.Engaging and accessible for nonexpert concerned citizens, The Octopus in the Parking Garage empowers readers to face the climate crisis and shows what we can do to adapt and thrive.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAdaptation (Biology). 0aHuman beingsxEffect of climate on. 0aNatural disastersxRisk assessment. 0aResilience (Ecology). 7aSCIENCE / Global Warming & Climate Change.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311074967008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Medicine and Life Sciences 2023 Englishz978311131921608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Medicine and Life Sciences 2023z9783111318615oZDB-23-DPM0 cprintz978023120354840uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/verc2035440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231555104423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231555104/original  a978-3-11-074967-0  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-131921-6  EBOOK PACKAGE Medicine and Life Sciences 2023 Englishb2023  a978-3-11-131929-